text:
happy kwanzaa!

are you familiar with kwanzaa?  it is a nonreligious celebration of family and optimism for the new year.  nice for us all to celebrate!

kwanzaa uses a kinara (similar to a menorah) to light a candle each day celebrating the seven principles - unity, self-determination, collective responsibility, cooperative economics, purpose, creativity, and faith.  good principles to reflect on, end the year with, and begin the new year ‚ù§Ô∏è

text:
i've watched the qspiracy since the beginning.

steve bannon left the wh august last year and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences? church militant, anyone?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit a hijacked party is obviously just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt with the brave bunch known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can easily contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this opportunity and messes with the boombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on me me me bed. obviously someone has a lot to lose when none of the us intelligence agencies ends this loonatic travesty.

qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that joseph goebbels would have died for. it is clear that stuff like pizzagate‚Ñ¢ was testing and groundwork for the 2016 election and since it proved to be very effective it is used still.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are helpless with the content - no way they are going to risk their business by taking responsibility.

there is absolutely no way that gop isn't aware of what is going on - after all cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same facebook user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got from cambridge analytica.

trump is truly playing along with his tweets, gestures and words. the bigger issue still is that republicans willingly piggybacked this lunacy while campaigning for the midterms and still keep abusing the faith of their fellow men.

this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

text:
do you trust me? i know you may not know me very well, but i promise you i would not steer you wrong.
.
these are all real pictures of real women {my personal real friends} who have made real changes. changes you can clearly see on the outside, and huge changes on the inside which you can‚Äôt physically see.
.
we work together every day to support, uplift and motivate each other to practice healthy living every day. some days are better than others because we have found a for life lifestyle‚Äî 
and that‚Äôs real life!
.
but we always have our community to help us through the hard days {and sometimes seasons}, we always have a plan that we know works for the long term, and we always have each other‚Äôs backs!
.
these are women who decided
‚Ä¢enough of the quick fixes
‚Ä¢enough of the yo-yo dieting
‚Ä¢enough of thinking they didn‚Äôt deserve to be a priority .
and they made a change
.
and you can too! make 2019 the year you decided to go for it‚Äî 
go for those changes for good‚Äî
for you!
.
and know when you are ready to make the choice, you don‚Äôt have to be on the journey alone!
.
.

this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies.

they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green
devil's bargain: steve bannon, donald trump, and the storming of the presidency

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‚Äòugh. totally ugly‚Äô to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it‚Äôs worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don‚Äôt necessarily know it‚Äôs being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it‚Äôs worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you‚Äôre doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people‚Äôs personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn‚Äôt have seen, and couldn‚Äôt have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, ‚Äúwould work for anyone‚Äù. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they‚Äôre mercenaries. they‚Äôll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it‚Äôs an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing ‚Äì at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public ‚Äì our intimate family connections, our ‚Äúlikes‚Äù, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that‚Äôs expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - i‚Äôve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now i‚Äôm about to go back, knowing what i know, and we‚Äôre about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trump‚Äôs election, trumpeted the return of their ‚Äúpopulist hero‚Äù on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publication‚Äôs announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if there‚Äôs any confusion out there, let me clear it up: i‚Äôm leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents ‚Äì on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - i‚Äôve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now i‚Äôm about to go back, knowing what i know, and we‚Äôre about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trump‚Äôs election, trumpeted the return of their ‚Äúpopulist hero‚Äù on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publication‚Äôs announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if there‚Äôs any confusion out there, let me clear it up: i‚Äôm leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents ‚Äì on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - i‚Äôve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now i‚Äôm about to go back, knowing what i know, and we‚Äôre about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trump‚Äôs election, trumpeted the return of their ‚Äúpopulist hero‚Äù on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publication‚Äôs announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if there‚Äôs any confusion out there, let me clear it up: i‚Äôm leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents ‚Äì on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - i‚Äôve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now i‚Äôm about to go back, knowing what i know, and we‚Äôre about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trump‚Äôs election, trumpeted the return of their ‚Äúpopulist hero‚Äù on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publication‚Äôs announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if there‚Äôs any confusion out there, let me clear it up: i‚Äôm leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents ‚Äì on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text:
veƒçeras od 19 sati oƒçekuje nas gigantomahija ili krokodilov duel u tri runde na temu: "#metoo pokret u svetu i kod nas: novo osna≈æivanje ili novi puritanizam." uƒçestvuju: dubravka stojanoviƒá i biljana srbljanoviƒá.
cena ulaznice u pretprodaji 300 dinara a 500 dinara s konzumacijom jednog piƒáa po izboru. cena ulaznice na vratima na dan dogaƒëaja 500 dinara s konzumacijom jednog piƒáa po izboru.
ulaznice se mogu kupiti u krokodilovom centru svakog dana od 10 do 22 ƒçasa izuzev nedeljom (od 16 do 22 ƒçasa).
pokret protiv seksualnog nasilja #metoo izazvao je brojne kontraverze tokom prethodne godine i mo≈æe se smatrati jednim od najva≈ænijih oznaƒçitelja godine koja je na izmaku.
ova inicijativa koju su pokrenule ≈ærtve seksualnog nasilja pro≈°irila se od sad na druge dr≈æave sveta, a nakon ≈°to su brojne i poznate glumice priznale da su na poƒçecima karijere bile ≈ærtve reditelja, kolega ili producenata pokret je dobio na globalnom zamahu. nakon ≈°to se otkrilo da su poznati i uticajni mu≈°karci, poput filmskog producenta harveya weinsteina seksualno zlostavljali glumice i koleginice, mnoge ≈æene su obelodanile sopstvene ispovesti.
iako je nesumnjivo reƒç o talasu novog osloboƒëenja, nesumnjivo preko potrebnog ≈æenama ≈°irom planete, ujedno je paralelno stvorena i atmosfera intenzivnog lova na ve≈°tice pa je opravdano pitanje opasnosti od predominacije novog oblika puritanizma koji vi≈°e od svih i svega zapravo ponajvi≈°e odgovara globalnom politiƒçkom i ekonomskom mejnstrimu. 
o pozitivnim i negativnim implikacijama ovog fenomena raspravljaƒáe istoriƒçarka dubravka stojanoviƒá i dramska spisateljica biljana srbljanoviƒá na novom izdanju gigantomahije, krokodilovog duela u tri runde.
--

text:
my idea of a nice hawaiian punch bowl - some #lebaneseredhash over some #goldengoat (relates back to maui wowie) dreamy and redolent of ginger. damn, hawaiian punch was the bomb diggity over snowcones. violent punching aside, or do we need to #metoo the intimate partner violence depicted in those cartoons? can i like hawaiian punch while protesting the jovial yet sinister depiction of the creepy little bully repeatedly dishing out blows to the head of his target? #ambivalentmuch a person who seems to exhibit signs of #cte i might add. yeah no. a straw hat and tourist shirt doesn't make your punch cool. i feel like ashton would sit him down and say, 'bro - too far, man...' and now we have to live with things like kardashians (omg stop making us contour it looks awful in profile) and juice bars. look like a clone. get a non-beverage, a bioplastic cup of fastwalking superiority to go. no. i want the stuff on the bourgeois table. if you're serving me a green beverage it'd better be lime kool-aid. not some kale-flavored colonic decontamination concoction masquerading as a proper meal. .
.
what's the word on hawaiian punch? tainted love or don't be a chucklehead it's delicious and no cartoons never hurt nobody whatsoevers. .
.
.
i may or may not have had a bunch of dark chocolate which is possibly the source of enough caffeine to make the squirrel squad in my head react like meth house rats to the whole ethics of beverages line of inquiry. and one final tangent: diabetes. we drank a lot of packages of that stuff. sure is something to ponder going forward. do i really need more food dye in my life? #hawaiianpunch #eatclean #oldfolksmoke #coololdstuff #meditationart #cannabis 
#cannabisismymedicine @wave_maker_ ¬©2018

text:
i can‚Äôt believe i will be walking across the stage to receive my diploma this may üéì. for years i was told by my ex that i couldn‚Äôt do it, that i was a ‚Äúsheep‚Äù for attending school & would never make a difference in my life. he resented the fact that i had the drive & ambition he didn‚Äôt to get it done. i was learning things he didn‚Äôt know, which hurt his ego. he never supported me & would try to convince me that i was the idiot & he was in fact superior to me. he always put me beneath him. 
no matter how many fights we had, how many times i fell to the floor in tears & pain, how sick i got from the stress, how he terrified me with his rage, how many times he made me feel worthless & pathetic, i was determined to graduate. & i did, despite everything thrown at me. 
despite dealing with the verbal, emotional, & mental abuse, my crohn‚Äôs disease, anxiety, insomnia, ptsd, chronic fatigue, tight finances, struggling with jobs, staying up late studying, and taking difficult classes like organic chemistry & failing the first time. 
despite everything, i came out on top. 
i am so proud of everything i‚Äôve accomplished. 
if you are feeling like giving up, don‚Äôt. 
you‚Äôve got this. 
you know you‚Äôve got this. üí™
don‚Äôt let anyone else tell you different. üíï

text:
are you happy with yourself?...
it took insane amount of courage to post a picture of myself without makeup. for some people it may not be a big deal but for someone who has suffered from bullying and had an extremly tough time loving herself, it is a quite a big deal to post a picture of something that was once her greatest insecurity. by no means am i implying that there is something wrong with the idea of covering up or doing makeup. its has helped me through my toughest days and made me think that i finally look pretty. read that sentence again. i said that it made me "think" i look pretty. which brings me to my main point that its all in the mind. once i started looking at myself in the mirror from a new prespective i realized that i am beyond beautiful even with or without the luxury of makeup. my motive is to make other individuals realize the same thing. this can only be done if the definition of beauty itself is altered in our minds.

#acne #loveyourself #redefinepretty #metoo #doyouboo

text:
when i had to make the decision to stay in new zealand for longer i resented the circumstances around it, and it felt like forever.

but now there‚Äôs hardly any time left.

it‚Äôs so nice to be here. in a place where everything wrong that happened to me over there takes hardly any explanation to people.

in a place where what you see is more like what you get, instead of what you see being some carefully crafted mirage designed to conceal how ugly the situation really is.

it was driven home while i was here; the entire nation visibly in mourning for a murdered english tourist, from people in the street to the prime-minister.

how could this happen here, this isn‚Äôt who we want to be. we are so sorry. we offered no excuses, looked long and hard at ourselves, resolved to do better, to let the story live on to that end.

it doesn‚Äôt happen that way other way around. when our women die over there. it barely makes a ripple in a society with an undertow so vicious you have to be caught by it before you believe it could ever exist.

i can‚Äôt remember if i wrote about the kiwi woman i met by chance at the wedding i went to. whose colleagues in london murdered her cat and draped it over her doorway when she made a formal complaint about racial discrimination at her workplace. she came back here, of course.

i can‚Äôt remember if i wrote about the kiwi woman hired into a role as a producer only to be given admin and low level editing work, whose employers exploited the two-years they have to harass and violate human rights at will in the workplace to humiliate her until she quit. she was only hired to be a pretty thing. she stayed over there, she had enough industry contacts to.

i can‚Äôt remember if i wrote about the kiwi programme manager, who took a male junior staff member with her into a meeting with uk stakeholders. she was the only woman in the room. the men addressed all their questions to the young man. he walked out of the meeting in disgust. they spoke to her then.
.
‚Äúi hear from a lot of ex-pat kiwis with stories from the uk like yours.‚Äù tell me about it.

i‚Äôd tell you about it.

but i wake up every morning with these thick hands tightly around my throat.

coming of age in a culture that demands women be as small, quiet, and compliant as possible‚Äîlike a porcelain dove that will also have sex with you‚Äîwriter and humorist lindy west quickly discovered that she was anything but. 
from a painfully shy childhood in which she tried, unsuccessfully, to hide her big body and even bigger opinions; to her public war with stand-up comedians over rape jokes; to her struggle to convince herself, and then the world, that fat people have value; to her accidental activism and never-ending battle royale with internet trolls, lindy narrates her life with a blend of humor and pathos that manages to make a trip to the abortion clinic funny and wring tears out of a story about diarrhea.

with inimitable good humor, vulnerability, and boundless charm, lindy boldly shares how to survive in a world where not all stories are created equal and not all bodies are treated with equal respect, and how to weather hatred, loneliness, harassment, and loss‚Äîand walk away laughing. shrill provocatively dissects what it means to become self-aware the hard way, to go from wanting to be silent and invisible to earning a living defending the silenced in all caps.

text:
summing up 2018üòÖ
i saw a couple of friends do this cool move in their wheelchairs where they put their arms behind and balance on two wheels. it looked so cool i thought i'd give it a go. then i remembered i don't have triceps so instead, i fell back and struck this awesome pose.¬†
i have to say, best place i've found to fall over like this - canada. i was immediately surrounded by 10 lovely guys who lifted me back inü•∞ üíïworst place - good old new zealand. the one time i fell out, i lay crumpled on the ground and a truckie drove past, hooted and gave me the thumbs up lol... typical 'do it yourself' kiwi attitude! ü•ùü§îü•¥sometimes i kinda wish people would offer to help but doesn't happen much here, and i guess it's because many are scared i'll be offended because i can 'do it my-bloody-self'. truth is, sometimes in life, a hand is what we need, and if anyone ever offers to help me, even with getting my chair in and out of my car or grabbing a can off the supermarket shelf instead of me throwing something at it to knock it down... i'll usually gratefully accept help. if i'm feeling ultra independent that day, i'll decline but always with a smile and a thank you, because i realise they are 1. trying to be helpful 2. totally out of their comfort zone and up for abuse from what could be 'an angry cripple'. people just want to help, it's rare here, not because we aren't a caring bunch, we are, but we are also terrified of offending people. my advice, ask someone like me if they'd like a hand, if they tell you to 'f' off, don't take it personally, just know you tried to help, you have a beautiful heart and although your kindness wasn't needed, it may well be next time. #pose #fallen #tryingtobecool #fail #funny #laughter #smile #weird #help #redhair #redhead #wheelchair #spinalcordinjury #wheels #summer #newzealand #grass #2018

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‚Äòugh. totally ugly‚Äô to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it‚Äôs worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don‚Äôt necessarily know it‚Äôs being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it‚Äôs worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you‚Äôre doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people‚Äôs personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn‚Äôt have seen, and couldn‚Äôt have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, ‚Äúwould work for anyone‚Äù. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they‚Äôre mercenaries. they‚Äôll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it‚Äôs an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing ‚Äì at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public ‚Äì our intimate family connections, our ‚Äúlikes‚Äù, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that‚Äôs expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
i've watched the qspiracy since the beginning.

steve bannon left the wh august last year and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences? church militant, anyone?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit a hijacked party is obviously just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt with the brave bunch known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can easily contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this opportunity and messes with the boombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on me me me bed. obviously someone has a lot to lose when none of the us intelligence agencies ends this loonatic travesty.

qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that joseph goebbels would have died for. it is clear that stuff like pizzagate‚Ñ¢ was testing and groundwork for the 2016 election and since it proved to be very effective it is used still.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are helpless with the content - no way they are going to risk their business by taking responsibility.

there is absolutely no way that gop isn't aware of what is going on - after all cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same facebook user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got from cambridge analytica.

trump is truly playing along with his tweets, gestures and words. the bigger issue still is that republicans willingly piggybacked this lunacy while campaigning for the midterms and still keep abusing the faith of their fellow men.

this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‚Äòugh. totally ugly‚Äô to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it‚Äôs worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don‚Äôt necessarily know it‚Äôs being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it‚Äôs worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you‚Äôre doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people‚Äôs personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn‚Äôt have seen, and couldn‚Äôt have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, ‚Äúwould work for anyone‚Äù. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they‚Äôre mercenaries. they‚Äôll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it‚Äôs an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing ‚Äì at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public ‚Äì our intimate family connections, our ‚Äúlikes‚Äù, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that‚Äôs expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

millions of people‚Äôs personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn‚Äôt have seen, and couldn‚Äôt have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, ‚Äúwould work for anyone‚Äù. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subve elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they‚Äôre mercenaries. they‚Äôll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it‚Äôs an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing ‚Äì at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public ‚Äì our intimate family connections, our ‚Äúlikes‚Äù, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that‚Äôs expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

a few months later, in autumn 2013, wylie met steve bannon. at the time, he was editor-in-chief of breitbart, which he had brought to britain to support his friend nigel farage in his mission to take britain out of the european union.

what was he like? - smart, says wylie. - interesting. really interested in ideas. he‚Äôs the only straight man i‚Äôve ever talked to about intersectional feminist theory. he saw its relevance straightaway to the oppressions that conservative, young white men feel.

wylie meeting bannon was the moment petrol was poured on a flickering flame. wylie lives for ideas. he speaks 19 to the dozen for hours at a time. he had a theory to prove. and at the time, this was a purely intellectual problem. politics was like fashion, he told bannon.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
cambridge analytica, which was shut down earlier this year following an investigation by the observer, was the political marketing firm headed by trump‚Äôs former key adviser, steve bannon, and owned by hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. it also used user information obtained without authorisation in early 2014 ‚Äì including cultural preferences such as fashion and music ‚Äì to create a system that could single out voters in order to expose them to specific political advertising.

prior to the company‚Äôs role on trump‚Äôs election campaign, wylie had been its director of research. recalling his first meeting with bannon, he explained how fashion was one of the many things they examined, along with ‚Äújudith butler, foucault and nature of our fractured self‚Äù. he said the pair discussed the difference between crocs and chanel‚Äôs little black dress as analogous for the fashion spectrum ‚Äì which would become a blueprint for how the firm used fashion preferences later on.

wylie went onto to criticise the fashion industry for creating a ‚Äúpre-existing cultural foundation which allowed the alt-right to grow over that time period‚Äù. he conceded that while cambridge analytica ‚Äúexploited the cultural narratives that the fashion and culture industry put out‚Äù, the fashion industry was responsible for creating those cultural narratives in the first place. he added: ‚Äúwe need new narratives in culture, and to do a better job of showing more diversity‚Äù in order to direct politics along a different route.

according to the data obtained (the majority of which came from us users), certain fans of american denim brands such as wrangler, hollister and lee jeans could be more closely linked to low levels of openness and mistrust ‚Äì and therefore more likely to engage with pro-trump messaging.

morwenna ferrier
the guardian

text:
i've watched the qspiracy since the beginning.

steve bannon left the wh august last year and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences? church militant, anyone?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit a hijacked party is obviously just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt with the brave bunch known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can easily contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this opportunity and messes with the boombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on me me me bed. obviously someone has a lot to lose when none of the us intelligence agencies ends this loonatic travesty.

qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that joseph goebbels would have died for. it is clear that stuff like pizzagate‚Ñ¢ was testing and groundwork for the 2016 election and since it proved to be very effective it is used still.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are helpless with the content - no way they are going to risk their business by taking responsibility.

there is absolutely no way that gop isn't aware of what is going on - after all cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same facebook user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got from cambridge analytica.

trump is truly playing along with his tweets, gestures and words. the bigger issue still is that republicans willingly piggybacked this lunacy while campaigning for the midterms and still keep abusing the faith of their fellow men.

this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

text:
as 2019 approaches, we want to reflect on our event, ‚Äúcreating spaces‚Äù which addressed #violenceagainstwomen in our community (inspired by the global project of the same name by @oxfamcanada which is helping in 6 countries abroad on this topic). we was a great success, and we effectively created a safe space for a moderated, educational conversation on gender-based violence. 
we are proud to #believesurvivors & are thrilled to reflect on the many victories for survivors this year, starting with the ‚Äúsilence breakers‚Äù (time person of the year 2017) to the women‚Äôs usa gymnastics team for their victory to the #metoo campaign in general, among many others. we are also reflecting on losses that continue to occur when people in positions of power perpetuate the problem of #genderbasedviolence. 
going into #2019, we are ready to take on the good fight. human rights for human kind. 
#womensrightsarehumanrights

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
at a hearing before the senate judiciary committee, christopher wylie described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election. - one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters. the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like ‚Äòdrain the swamp‚Äô or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the ‚Äòdeep state‚Äô that weren‚Äôt necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement.

text:
i've watched the qspiracy since the beginning.

steve bannon left the wh august last year and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences? church militant, anyone?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit a hijacked party is obviously just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt with the brave bunch known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can easily contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this opportunity and messes with the boombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on me me me bed. obviously someone has a lot to lose when none of the us intelligence agencies ends this loonatic travesty.

qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that joseph goebbels would have died for. it is clear that stuff like pizzagate‚Ñ¢ was testing and groundwork for the 2016 election and since it proved to be very effective it is used still.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are helpless with the content - no way they are going to risk their business by taking responsibility.

there is absolutely no way that gop isn't aware of what is going on - after all cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same facebook user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got from cambridge analytica.

trump is truly playing along with his tweets, gestures and words. the bigger issue still is that republicans willingly piggybacked this lunacy while campaigning for the midterms and still keep abusing the faith of their fellow men.

this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

in 2014, steve bannon ‚Äì then executive chairman of the ‚Äúalt-right‚Äù news network breitbart ‚Äì was christopher wylie‚Äôs boss. and robert mercer, the secretive us hedge-fund billionaire and republican donor, was cambridge analytica‚Äôs investor. and the idea they bought into was to bring big data and social media to an established military methodology ‚Äì ‚Äúinformation operations‚Äù ‚Äì then turn it on the us electorate.

cambridge analytica‚Äôs parent company, scl, had won contracts with the us state department and was pitching to the pentagon, and wylie was genuinely freaked out. - it‚Äôs insane, he told me one night. - the company has created psychological profiles of 230 million americans. and now they want to work with the pentagon? it‚Äôs like nixon on steroids.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
in 2014, steve bannon ‚Äì then executive chairman of the ‚Äúalt-right‚Äù news network breitbart ‚Äì was christopher wylie‚Äôs boss. and robert mercer, the secretive us hedge-fund billionaire and republican donor, was cambridge analytica‚Äôs investor. and the idea they bought into was to bring big data and social media to an established military methodology ‚Äì ‚Äúinformation operations‚Äù ‚Äì then turn it on the us electorate.

cambridge analytica‚Äôs parent company, scl, had won contracts with the us state department and was pitching to the pentagon, and wylie was genuinely freaked out. - it‚Äôs insane, he told me one night. - the company has created psychological profiles of 230 million americans. and now they want to work with the pentagon? it‚Äôs like nixon on steroids.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
.
many moons ago, each of us embarked on an unfamiliar journey. not knowing if it would lead us to fulfillment. yet still, we had faith. we hit rock bottom too many times to count and prayed that better days were ahead.
our road to ascension was a tortuous one. it brought the darkest depths of our souls to the light. but never once did we forget how hard we'd have to fight to survive facing our shadows in plain sight.it took everything we had to make it through. to make that sparkle in our eyes reignite.
yet we made it.
we went with the flow of life.
then we became the flow,
and took flight.

cambridge analytica‚Äôs parent company, scl, had won contracts with the us state department and was pitching to the pentagon, and wylie was genuinely freaked out. - it‚Äôs insane, he told me one night. - the company has created psychological profiles of 230 million americans. and now they want to work with the pentagon? it‚Äôs like nixon on steroids.

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

take time to affirm and appreciate yourself everyday.

text:
take a good look at the 33rd! edition of the #economist telling you in your face the state of the staged world in the upcoming episode of this ritualistic reality show that we have all unwillingly taken part in.
what does a stork usually carry in a bag? yeah, a baby...only this time the "product" has a barcode and a serial number on it as it is shipped from a supposed poor region (poor weirdo ghandi) of the world to the western land of the electric cars...someone should get on that serial number to decode it...and that vitruvian man with a night vision/virtual reality gear on...
‚Ä¢
all the satanic mirrored spells aside, "putin's pipelines" is written right above the depiction of the four horsemen of the apocalypse to come at the end of the world symbolizing conquest, war, famine, and plague/death...
‚Ä¢
i don't even wanna talk about the baseball, the "cell"phone, that hemp leaf and that fucking scale with 4=5 people on each side, 2+2=5 concept from 1984 programming written by a bbc whore of a mason with a fake name george whorewell...
‚Ä¢ 
there is a ton of symbolism, like the one-eyed black and white panda (china) sitting between putin-trump, the duality of the two voting boxes representing the fake political systems with south african and indian flags (with british ties that claimed independence) on them as opposed to that brexit bulldog, the pinocchio with an arrow on his face, the indian elephant tusk going up like a chart maybe representing the booming economy/tech of india, all those written headlines up there with as clear as daylight numeralogy attached to these letters which i can't even wanna start looking into anymore, the #metoo tattoo, that amarillo that symbolizes protection and boundaries with its protective shell reminding us to protect ourselves and a lot more hidden layers of esoteric meanings and geometry behind this...
‚Ä¢
many regards to my brother @loong_distance for exchanging ideas and decoding techniques...love how a healthy mind thinks...
‚Ä¢
p.s. i dunno who are the two bitches at the bottom, i can't make anything out of ghandi with that salt-making device and can't read what's written above that elephant under that satellite looking thingy .

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

tonight is our last in tel aviv for this winter trip. luckily for us, the 25th of december is like any other day here, which means the bars are open and the cocktails are flowing. at the same time, we‚Äôd love to spread a little bit of christmas cheer from one of our favorite establishments from the past week‚Äîthank you to both bar manager @morben29 and
bartender @eldar_gabay92 for making @223tlv feel like a home away from home. using several flavor components representative of israeli culture and agriculture, @arielleizgold built an incredible concoction to battle the scorching summer heat and cozy up with during the cooler winter months. his tlv heat is a year-round crowd pleaser at @223tlv as a result, and presented as the perfect christmas present. while we‚Äôre leaving for barcelona in the morning, we have plenty more to share from our time in tel aviv over the coming weeks. for now, check out the recipe below, stay warm, and have a merry christmas.
-
tlv heat

40 ml ouzo
10 ml elderflower liqueur @stgermaindrinks
15 ml fig jam
20 ml lime juice
20 ml orange juice
2 dashes sheba tincture

garnish: dehydrated orange, dehydrated lime, sesame candy, sprig of mint, and sprinkle over top with powdered sugar

glassware: enamel red & white mug

method: shake briefly and dirty strain into the mug. fill with crushed ice, garnish as above, and add a straw for easy imbibing.

creator: ariel leizgold @arielleizgold, owner & master mixologist of @223tlv
-
a job well done to @arielleizgold and the whole @223tlv team for building a craft cocktail program that‚Äôs both the first and longest-running of its kind in israel. thank you for the incredible experience. #keepitcrafted

wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text: christmas can be hard for many. my heart goes out to all the people who are struggling beneath the surface these holidays. whether if it‚Äôs a lost loved one, depression, a broken home, anxiety, an eating disorder, a broken marriage, abuse, addiction.... it‚Äôs hard to find joy when your heart is hurting. remember this truth today - ‚Äúwhen my smile gets a little forced, when i feel tired upon waking and when i start to bully myself within my own mind. i will try to remember whose birthday i am celebrating today (christ‚Äôs), and see past the tinsel, turkey and trimmings. when jesus left his stable and entered into his ministry, his focus was not solely on the happy, the blessed and the ones who had it all together. he focused on lepers and sinners, the poor and helpless. this christmas i will remember jesus as the light. he is a light which is made to help those who suffer darkness.‚Äù jesus taught us all to not forget those who are suffering or facing a difficult time in life, and that it's not what we get that defines us but what we give to others that tells the real story about who we are. merry christmas everyone. if you're one of those hurting at christmas this year, know you aren't forgotten and that others care about you. you are loved. you are not alone. ‚ù§Ô∏è

text:
qanon fans are applying this same participatory behavior that we have celebrated in fiction fandom to real-world political drama. and why not? the boundaries between politics and entertainment have been collapsing for years. the entire trump presidency operates like reality tv, completely divorced from any real stakes or substance.

that‚Äôs what makes this all so terrifying. do these people really believe that tom hanks and hillary clinton are personally running a massive pedophilia ring? really??? but consider this: trump announced at a rally this week that the farmers being harmed by his stupid trade war had told him ‚Äúwe can take it.‚Äù no actual farmers said that to him. we all know that. but it‚Äôs a little thing, just part of the story we are all interacting with.

the pulsating heart of the qanon theory is not a lunatic fringe denying the real consequences of a failing presidency. the heart of it is a devoted fan base constructing elaborate theories to make the story more fun and engaging. and if you start from the premise that nothing government does matters, then it‚Äôs easy to come along for the ride. there‚Äôs no real difference between hillary clinton and the smoke monster. they‚Äôre both just characters on the television.

that‚Äôs what alarms me most about the growth of qanon. it‚Äôs not that these people are unhinged and possibly armed. it‚Äôs that we‚Äôve lost the capacity to treat civics, governance, and public affairs as though they have actual stakes with actual consequences. the premise of the trump presidency is that nothing matters, so you should root for your side and heckle the opposing team. he encourages his supporters to treat democrats and journalists like a rival fan base.

david karpf

text:
shecan: the scene presenter salma el-wardany

the scene is on¬† bbc radio london with evening shows from monday 26 november as six new presenters take over from 8-10pm, fronted by six presenters with backgrounds from across london‚Äôs cultural, music, comedy and spoken word worlds.
#bbcradiolondon editor davidrobey, says:‚Äúthe scene will be a platform for london‚Äôs community arts, entertainment and cultural activities, featuring new talent and emerging artists, performers and creators. #aurie, claira, judi, jasmine, salma and lionheart have first-hand experience and knowledge of what‚Äôs happening in london‚Äôs creative and diverse communities which they will bring to listeners every weekday evening on the scene.‚Äù alt wanted to find out more about writer, poet, spoken word artist and tedx speaker salma el-wardany.¬†pictured salma and co-host #lionheart.

alt: woman are being given a platform and the focus on women has catapulted, do you think we can sustain this movement and can it be credited to the #timesup and #metoo movements?

salma: i think it would be unfair of the efforts of feminists over the decades to solely credit the current shifts to just those two movements, especially since they are movements that have been dominated by white, let‚Äôs be honest, rich, women. it is not just a financially elite section of society that gets to make change, but rather it is all of us that have contributed from all socio-economic and cultural backgrounds. those two movements have been incredible at igniting popular discourse and pushing some really difficult conversations into the spotlight, but i think #women taking, and i use that word as opposed to giving, the platforms they deserve can be credited to a multitude of reasons, and a huge one being that we‚Äôre no longer willing to swallow silence. we‚Äôve reached such a boiling point of anger, frustration and hurt that we‚Äôve almost snapped. have gone past the point of tiptoeing around societal expectations and are not holding back anymore, and that‚Äôs such a wonderful space to be in. read full interview www.alt-africa.com

text:
qanon fans are applying this same participatory behavior that we have celebrated in fiction fandom to real-world political drama. and why not? the boundaries between politics and entertainment have been collapsing for years. the entire trump presidency operates like reality tv, completely divorced from any real stakes or substance.

that‚Äôs what makes this all so terrifying. do these people really believe that tom hanks and hillary clinton are personally running a massive pedophilia ring? really??? but consider this: trump announced at a rally this week that the farmers being harmed by his stupid trade war had told him ‚Äúwe can take it.‚Äù no actual farmers said that to him. we all know that. but it‚Äôs a little thing, just part of the story we are all interacting with.

the pulsating heart of the qanon theory is not a lunatic fringe denying the real consequences of a failing presidency. the heart of it is a devoted fan base constructing elaborate theories to make the story more fun and engaging. and if you start from the premise that nothing government does matters, then it‚Äôs easy to come along for the ride. there‚Äôs no real difference between hillary clinton and the smoke monster. they‚Äôre both just characters on the television.

that‚Äôs what alarms me most about the growth of qanon. it‚Äôs not that these people are unhinged and possibly armed. it‚Äôs that we‚Äôve lost the capacity to treat civics, governance, and public affairs as though they have actual stakes with actual consequences. the premise of the trump presidency is that nothing matters, so you should root for your side and heckle the opposing team. he encourages his supporters to treat democrats and journalists like a rival fan base.

david karpf
medium

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
i've watched the qspiracy since the beginning.

steve bannon left the wh august last year and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences? church militant, anyone?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit a hijacked party is obviously just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt with the brave bunch known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can easily contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this opportunity and messes with the boombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on me me me bed. obviously someone has a lot to lose when none of the us intelligence agencies ends this loonatic travesty.

qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that joseph goebbels would have died for. it is clear that stuff like pizzagate‚Ñ¢ was testing and groundwork for the 2016 election and since it proved to be very effective it is used still.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are helpless with the content - no way they are going to risk their business by taking responsibility.

there is absolutely no way that gop isn't aware of what is going on - after all cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same facebook user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got from cambridge analytica.

wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
what a day. where to start?

after last night 3 people asking me in a q&a if i am pregnant, to waking up to so ma y messages today about so many women and their challenges and how hurtful it was for them to have been asked the same question especially with all their struggles in that area my heart is aching. all of us project. we project our feelings, we project was is going on in our lives and sometimes we assume that others are having a similar experience as we are. unless we personally either say the wrong thing to someone or experience someome saying the wrong thing to us, it is hard to understand why this is not an overly sensitive thing to do by not commenting...its the right thing to do. aside for all this, the body shame that comes along with all this is beyond destructive. why is it that when someone comments on someones body (belly in specific) do some women feel horrible about themselves, some throw that outfit out, some crash diet, some wear a girdle every day, some cry and feel alone and "fat" and even "ugly" when people assume they are pregnant. and many said that after they said very clearly they arent pregnant "are you sure? but you look it" so so many have gotten such remarks! why?! i believe its lack of education. possible a social issue, insecurity. whatever it is, it hurts. women. need to be there to lift eachother up, not knock eachother down, shame. no body was created the same. and it is more than okay to have a belly that is not flat. it is normal. all bodies are beautiful, all womens bodies should be respected and not talked about. curious to hear your thoughts. let's lift eachother up! 
photo @pictureitbyniri

#bodypositivity #bodyshaming #womenempowerment #metoo #spreadawareness #postpartum #love #awareness

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

steve bannon left the wh august last year and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences? church militant, anyone?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit a hijacked party is obviously just business as usual.

i've watched the qspiracy since the beginning.

steve bannon left the wh august last year and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences? church militant, anyone?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit a hijacked party is obviously just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt with the brave bunch known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can easily contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this opportunity and messes with the boombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on me me me bed. obviously someone has a lot to lose when none of the us intelligence agencies ends this loonatic travesty.

qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that joseph goebbels would have died for. it is clear that stuff like pizzagate‚Ñ¢ was testing and groundwork for the 2016 election and since it proved to be very effective it is used still.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are helpless with the content - no way they are going to risk their business by taking responsibility.

there is absolutely no way that gop isn't aware of what is going on - after all cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same facebook user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got from cambridge analytica.

trump is truly playing along with his tweets, gestures and words. the bigger issue still is that republicans willingly piggybacked this lunacy while campaigning for the midterms and still keep abusing the faith of their fellow men.

this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

text:
take a good look at the 33rd! edition of the #economist telling you in your face the state of the staged world in the upcoming episode of this ritualistic reality show that we have all unwillingly taken part in.
what does a stork usually carry in a bag? yeah, a baby...only this time the "product" has a barcode and a serial number on it as it is shipped from a supposed poor region (poor weirdo ghandi) of the world to the western land of the electric cars...someone should get on that serial number to decode it...and that vitruvian man with a night vision/virtual reality gear on...
‚Ä¢
all the satanic mirrored spells aside, "putin's pipelines" is written right above the depiction of the four horsemen of the apocalypse to come at the end of the world symbolizing conquest, war, famine, and plague/death...
‚Ä¢
i don't even wanna talk about the baseball, the "cell"phone, that hemp leaf and that fucking scale with 4=5 people on each side, 2+2=5 concept from 1984 programming written by a bbc whore of a mason with a fake name george whorewell...
‚Ä¢ 
there is a ton of symbolism, like the one-eyed black and white panda (china) sitting between putin-trump, the duality of the two voting boxes representing the fake political systems with south african and indian flags (with british ties that claimed independence) on them as opposed to that brexit bulldog, the pinocchio with an arrow on his face, the indian elephant tusk going up like a chart maybe representing the booming economy/tech of india, all those written headlines up there with as clear as daylight numeralogy attached to these letters which i can't even wanna start looking into anymore, the #metoo tattoo, that amarillo that symbolizes protection and boundaries with its protective shell reminding us to protect ourselves and a lot more hidden layers of esoteric meanings and geometry behind this...
‚Ä¢
many regards to my brother @loong_distance for exchanging ideas and decoding techniques...love how a healthy mind thinks...
‚Ä¢
p.s. i dunno who are the two bitches at the bottom, i can't make anything out of ghandi with that salt-making device and can't read what's written above that elephant under that satellite looking thingy ...
